# Flutter AI Toolkit Development Rules

## Project Context
This project uses Flutter AI Toolkit with Firebase AI (Gemini/Vertex AI) for building AI-powered chat applications.

## Code Style Rules

### Dart Conventions
- Use `const` constructors wherever possible
- Prefer `final` over `var` for immutable variables
- Use named parameters for functions with more than 2 parameters
- Follow lowerCamelCase for variables, functions, and parameters
- Follow UpperCamelCase for classes and types

### Widget Structure
- Keep widgets small and focused
- Extract reusable widgets into separate files
- Use `StatelessWidget` when state is not needed
- Prefer composition over inheritance

### Firebase AI Integration
```dart
// For prototyping (Gemini endpoint)
FirebaseAI.googleAI().generativeModel(model: 'gemini-2.5-flash')

// For production (Vertex AI endpoint)
FirebaseAI.vertexAI().generativeModel(model: 'gemini-2.5-flash')
```

### LlmChatView Configuration
```dart
LlmChatView(
  provider: FirebaseProvider(
    model: FirebaseAI.vertexAI().generativeModel(
      model: 'gemini-2.5-flash',
    ),
  ),
  // Optional: custom styling, attachments, voice input
)
```

## File Organization
- `lib/main.dart` - App entry with Firebase init
- `lib/screens/` - Screen widgets
- `lib/widgets/` - Reusable widgets
- `lib/services/` - Business logic
- `lib/models/` - Data models

## Error Handling
- Always handle async errors with try-catch
- Show user-friendly error messages
- Log errors for debugging

## Performance
- Use `const` widgets to prevent unnecessary rebuilds
- Implement proper state management
- Avoid expensive operations in build methods

## Testing
- Write unit tests for business logic
- Write widget tests for UI components
- Use mock providers for AI testing
